**Category 1: Membership & Tier Determination**

These rules fire first on every member interaction. They determine which
set of subsequent rules applies. Tier determination is immutable once
established and gates all eligibility and benefit calculations.

**1.0 --- Summary**

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**       **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ----------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-TIER-1       Tier 1 Determination       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions

  RULE-TIER-2       Tier 2 Determination       ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-TIER-3       Tier 3 Determination       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open

  RULE-CONTRIB-EE   Employee Contribution Rate ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open

  RULE-CONTRIB-ER   Employer Contribution Rate ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------

**1.1 --- RULE-TIER-1**

**RULE-TIER-1 Tier 1 Determination**

**Rule Statement:** A member is classified as Tier 1 if their initial
service began before September 1, 2004 AND they terminated service after
December 31, 1999.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(1) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• The \'terminates after Dec 31, 1999\' clause means members who
separated before 2000 are under a prior plan provision. Seed data must
not generate Tier 1 members with termination before Jan 1, 2000.

**Test Implications:** Boundary: hire Aug 31, 2004 = Tier 1; hire Sep 1,
2004 = Tier 2. Also test termination date clause (pre-2000 termination
should not produce Tier 1).

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 1 only (determination rule)

**1.2 --- RULE-TIER-2**

**RULE-TIER-2 Tier 2 Determination**

**Rule Statement:** A member is classified as Tier 2 if their initial
service began on or after September 1, 2004 but before July 1, 2011.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(2) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Boundary: hire Sep 1, 2004 = Tier 2; hire Jun 30,
2011 = Tier 2; hire Jul 1, 2011 = Tier 3.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 2 only (determination rule)

**1.3 --- RULE-TIER-3**

**RULE-TIER-3 Tier 3 Determination**

**Rule Statement:** A member is classified as Tier 3 if their initial
service first began on or after July 1, 2011.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(3) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Tier is determined by INITIAL hire date, not most recent. For
re-employment after retirement, RMC §18-408(j)(1) confirms new service
earns under Tier 3 formula regardless of original tier, but original
benefit retains original tier.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[TIER-REHIRE-01\] If a member quits (not retires) in Tier 2 era and
is rehired in Tier 3 era, which tier applies? Most likely: original tier
based on \'initial service\' language, but needs DERP confirmation.

**Test Implications:** Boundary: hire Jul 1, 2011 = Tier 3; hire Jun 30,
2011 = Tier 2. Test rehire scenario if DERP clarifies.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3 only (determination rule)

**1.4 --- RULE-CONTRIB-EE**

**RULE-CONTRIB-EE Employee Contribution Rate**

**Rule Statement:** Employee contributes 8.45% of gross salary, pretax.

**Source:** RMC §18-407(f)(1), effective January 1, 2023 **✅
CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• This is the current rate only. Historical rates needed for seed data
(8.45% since at least 2014; earlier rates unknown). For the rules
engine, only current rate matters.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[CONTRIB-HIST-01\] Historical employee contribution rate schedule
needed for realistic seed data generation spanning multiple decades. Low
priority --- does not affect rules engine.

**Test Implications:** Verify 8.45% applied to gross salary. Verify
pretax treatment.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**1.5 --- RULE-CONTRIB-ER**

**RULE-CONTRIB-ER Employer Contribution Rate**

**Rule Statement:** Employer contributes 17.95% of gross salary.

**Source:** RMC §18-407(e)(1), effective January 1, 2023 **✅
CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Same historical rate caveat as employee contribution. Approximate:
\~11% pre-2012, scaling to 17.95% current. These are estimates for seed
data, not verified rates.

**Test Implications:** Verify 17.95% applied to gross salary in
current-era calculations.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 2: Service Credit Calculation**

Service credit feeds both eligibility determination and benefit
calculation, but with different inclusion rules. The critical
distinction between earned and purchased service affects multiple
downstream rules.

**2.0 --- Summary**

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**           **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  --------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-SVC-EARNED       Earned Service Credit      ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open
                        Calculation                             

  RULE-SVC-PURCHASED    Purchased Service Credit   ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-SVC-SEPARATION   Service Credit Type        ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                        Separation                              
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**2.1 --- RULE-SVC-EARNED**

**RULE-SVC-EARNED Earned Service Credit Calculation**

**Rule Statement:** Earned service credit accumulates from actual
employment with covered employers, calculated from hire date to
termination/retirement date.

**Source:** RMC §18-402 (definitions), §18-409(a) (benefit calculation
references) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Service credit calculation method (year-month vs. exact day) is NOT
specified in the RMC. Our demo cases use year-month (months/12, e.g., 28
yrs 9 mo = 28.75). If DERP uses exact days, Robert Martinez would be
28.797 instead of 28.75.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-02\] \[CRITICAL\] How does DERP calculate partial years of
service credit? Year-month method (months/12) or exact day method
(days/365.25)? Affects every benefit calculation.

**Test Implications:** Test with known employment periods. Verify
calculation matches chosen method precisely. Must test both methods
until DERP confirms which one.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**2.2 --- RULE-SVC-PURCHASED**

**RULE-SVC-PURCHASED Purchased Service Credit**

**Rule Statement:** Purchased service credit counts toward benefit
CALCULATION only. It is explicitly EXCLUDED from: vesting, Rule of 75/85
determination, and IPR calculation.

**Source:** RMC §18-415(a) --- \'Cannot be used for vesting or
qualifying for different benefit category\' **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Critical test: member with purchased service must
show different totals for \'service for calculation\' vs \'service for
eligibility\'. Jennifer Kim (Case 2) is the primary test: 21.17 total
but 18.17 for Rule of 75. Test that IPR uses earned-only service.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**2.3 --- RULE-SVC-SEPARATION**

**RULE-SVC-SEPARATION Service Credit Type Separation**

**Rule Statement:** System must maintain separate tracking of earned,
purchased, military, and leave service credit types. Each type has
different applicability rules.

**Source:** RMC §18-415 (purchase provisions), §18-402 (definitions)
**✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Verify data model stores service credit by type.
Verify each usage point (eligibility, benefit calc, IPR) pulls the
correct subset.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 3: Eligibility Determination**

Eligibility rules gate the benefit calculation and determine whether
reductions apply. They must be evaluated in a strict hierarchy. The
interaction between age, service, tier, and minimum age requirements
creates the complexity.

**3.0 --- Summary**

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**             **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ----------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-VESTING            Vesting Requirement        ✅ CONFIRMED 2 assumptions

  RULE-NORMAL-RET         Normal Retirement          ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                          Eligibility                             

  RULE-RULE-OF-75         Rule of 75 Eligibility     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open

  RULE-RULE-OF-85         Rule of 85 Eligibility     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions

  RULE-EARLY-RET-T12      Early Retirement           ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                          Eligibility (Tiers 1 & 2)               

  RULE-EARLY-RET-T3       Early Retirement           ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                          Eligibility (Tier 3)                    

  RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T12   Early Retirement Reduction ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open
                          (Tiers 1 & 2)                           

  RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T3    Early Retirement Reduction ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                          (Tier 3)                                

  RULE-DEFERRED           Deferred Retirement        ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions

  RULE-ELIG-HIERARCHY     Eligibility Evaluation     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                          Order                                   
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**3.1 --- RULE-VESTING**

**RULE-VESTING Vesting Requirement**

**Rule Statement:** A member must have at least 5 years of credited
service to be vested and eligible for any retirement benefit. Members
appointed before January 1, 1987 required 10 years. Post-1987 but
pre-July 2011: 5 years or age 65 (whichever earlier). Post-July 2011: 5
years regardless of age.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(31) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• For POC scope, all synthetic members are post-1987 hires, so 5-year
vesting applies. The 10-year pre-1987 rule is documented but not
expected in demo cases.

• Vesting uses credited service (earned only? or earned + purchased?).
RMC §18-415(a) says purchased service cannot be used for vesting, so
vesting is earned-only.

**Test Implications:** Test at boundary: exactly 5.00 years = vested;
4.99 years = not vested. Verify purchased service excluded from vesting
count.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers (with era-specific variations)

**3.2 --- RULE-NORMAL-RET**

**RULE-NORMAL-RET Normal Retirement Eligibility**

**Rule Statement:** Age 65 or older AND at least 5 years of credited
service = normal retirement. Full unreduced benefit. Applies to all
tiers.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(20), §18-408 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: age 65 with 5 years = normal. Age 64 with
30 years = NOT normal (may be Rule of N). Age 65 with 4 years = NOT
eligible at all.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**3.3 --- RULE-RULE-OF-75**

**RULE-RULE-OF-75 Rule of 75 Eligibility**

**Rule Statement:** For Tiers 1 and 2: if age + earned service credit ≥
75 AND member has attained minimum age 55, member qualifies for
unreduced benefit. Rule must be attained while employed as active
member, prior to termination.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(20) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Rule uses EARNED service only (purchased excluded per
RULE-SVC-PURCHASED). Confirmed by §18-415(a).

• If member terminates after meeting the sum but before reaching age 55,
they must wait until age 55 to apply. They do NOT lose the Rule --- they
just cannot collect until minimum age.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-02-IMPACT\] The age + service sum depends on how partial
years are calculated. Year-month vs exact day could change whether a
member is 0.01 above or below 75.

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez (Case 1): 63 + 28.75 = 91.75 ≥ 75
✓. Jennifer Kim (Case 2): 55 + 18.17 = 73.17 \< 75 ✗. Test exact
boundary: sum = 75.00 exactly. Test sum = 74.99. Test member who meets
sum but is age 54 (must wait).

**Tier Applicability:** Tiers 1 and 2 only

**3.4 --- RULE-RULE-OF-85**

**RULE-RULE-OF-85 Rule of 85 Eligibility**

**Rule Statement:** For Tier 3: if age + earned service credit ≥ 85 AND
member has attained minimum age 60, member qualifies for unreduced
benefit. Rule must be attained while employed as active member, prior to
termination.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(20) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Same partial-year calculation dependency as Rule of 75.

**Test Implications:** David Washington (Case 3): 63 + 13.58 = 76.58 \<
85 ✗. Test exact boundary: sum = 85.00. Test member who meets sum at age
59 (must wait until 60).

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3 only

**3.5 --- RULE-EARLY-RET-T12**

**RULE-EARLY-RET-T12 Early Retirement Eligibility (Tiers 1 & 2)**

**Rule Statement:** Age 55 or older AND at least 5 years of credited
service AND does not meet normal retirement or Rule of 75. Benefit is
reduced.

**Source:** RMC §18-408, §18-409(b) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim (Case 2): age 55, 18+ years service,
does not meet Rule of 75 = early retirement. Test age 54 with 5 years =
NOT eligible.

**Tier Applicability:** Tiers 1 and 2

**3.6 --- RULE-EARLY-RET-T3**

**RULE-EARLY-RET-T3 Early Retirement Eligibility (Tier 3)**

**Rule Statement:** Age 60 or older AND at least 5 years of credited
service AND does not meet normal retirement or Rule of 85. Benefit is
reduced.

**Source:** RMC §18-408, §18-409(b) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** David Washington (Case 3): age 63, 13+ years,
does not meet Rule of 85 = early retirement. Test age 59 with 5 years =
NOT eligible for Tier 3 early.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3 only

**3.7 --- RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T12**

**RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T12 Early Retirement Reduction (Tiers 1 & 2)**

**Rule Statement:** Benefit reduced by 3% per year under age 65. Maximum
reduction 30% at age 55. Reduction is permanent. RMC provides statutory
lookup table by integer age (age 55 = 70%, age 56 = 73%, \... age 64 =
97%, age 65 = 100%).

**Source:** RMC §18-409(b) --- statutory table **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Integer-age approach confirmed by RMC statutory table. No monthly
proration. Decision 18 assumed completed years only --- RMC table
confirms this by listing integer ages only.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-03\] \[CRITICAL\] While the statutory table strongly implies
integer-age (no proration), DERP staff confirmation would eliminate any
ambiguity. E.g., does a member age 55 years 11 months get 70% or
something between 70% and 73%?

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim (Case 2): age 55, 10 years under 65,
30% reduction, benefit × 0.70 = \$1,633.07. Test each integer age from
55 to 64. Verify reduction is permanent (does not change at age 65).

**Tier Applicability:** Tiers 1 and 2

**3.8 --- RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T3**

**RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T3 Early Retirement Reduction (Tier 3)**

**Rule Statement:** Benefit reduced by 6% per year under age 65. Maximum
reduction 30% at age 60. Reduction is permanent. RMC provides statutory
lookup table (age 60 = 70%, age 61 = 76%, \... age 64 = 94%, age 65 =
100%).

**Source:** RMC §18-409(b) --- statutory table **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Same integer-age approach as Tiers 1/2. Note: Tier 3 table increments
are 6% (not uniform --- 70, 76, 82, 88, 94, 100).

**Test Implications:** David Washington (Case 3): age 63, 2 years under
65, 12% reduction, benefit × 0.88. Test each integer age from 60 to 64.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3 only

**3.9 --- RULE-DEFERRED**

**RULE-DEFERRED Deferred Retirement**

**Rule Statement:** Vested member who terminates employment before
reaching any retirement eligibility. Benefits calculated based on
service and salary at termination. Must wait until reaching eligibility
age to begin payments. If application deadline missed (30 days),
automatically classified as deferred.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(10), §18-408 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Automatic deferred classification after 30-day deadline is confirmed
by RMC --- no appeal or extension in statute.

**Test Implications:** Test: vested member age 50 terminates = deferred.
Test: member misses 30-day application deadline = forced deferred.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**3.10 --- RULE-ELIG-HIERARCHY**

**RULE-ELIG-HIERARCHY Eligibility Evaluation Order**

**Rule Statement:** Eligibility is evaluated in strict order: (1) Tier
determination, (2) Age at retirement, (3) Service credit separation, (4)
Vesting check, (5) Normal retirement check, (6) Rule of 75/85 check, (7)
Early retirement check, (8) Deferred if none met. First qualifying
category applies.

**Source:** Derived from RMC structure; evaluation order is
architectural decision documented in
noui-derp-service-retirement-process.md **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• A member who qualifies for both normal retirement (age 65+) and Rule
of 75 should be classified as normal retirement. The hierarchy prevents
double-classification but the benefit amount is identical.

**Test Implications:** Test member who meets multiple categories (age
65, Rule of 75 met). Verify single classification returned. Test all
four demo cases produce correct eligibility type.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 4: Benefit Calculation**

The core calculation engine. Every formula, every intermediate value,
and every rounding decision must be verifiable to the penny against hand
calculations. This is where pension administration demonstrates its core
competency.

**4.0 --- Summary**

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**            **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ---------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-AMS-WINDOW        AMS Averaging Period       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open

  RULE-AMS-CALC          AMS Calculation Method     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open

  RULE-LEAVE-PAYOUT      Leave Payout Inclusion     ✅ CONFIRMED 2 assumptions

  RULE-FURLOUGH          Furlough Impact on AMS     ⚠️ ASSUMED   1 open

  RULE-BENEFIT-T1        Tier 1 Benefit Formula     ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-BENEFIT-T2        Tier 2 Benefit Formula     ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-BENEFIT-T3        Tier 3 Benefit Formula     ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-REDUCTION-APPLY   Early Retirement Reduction ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                         Application                             

  RULE-ROUNDING          Calculation Rounding       ⚠️ ASSUMED   1 open
                         Strategy                                
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**4.1 --- RULE-AMS-WINDOW**

**RULE-AMS-WINDOW AMS Averaging Period**

**Rule Statement:** AMS uses the highest consecutive months of
pensionable salary. Tiers 1 & 2: 36 consecutive months. Tier 3: 60
consecutive months.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(1-3) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Period must be consecutive (no gaps). System must search ALL possible
windows to find the highest average.

• How partial months at start/end of employment are handled is not
specified in the RMC. Our assumption: only complete months are included.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-AMS-01\] How are partial months at start or end of employment
handled in AMS window? Include at prorated amount, or exclude?

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim (Case 2): 36-month window, AMS =
\$7,347.62. David Washington (Case 3): 60-month window. Verify window
slides to find highest average, not just most recent.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers (window size varies)

**4.2 --- RULE-AMS-CALC**

**RULE-AMS-CALC AMS Calculation Method**

**Rule Statement:** For each possible consecutive window of N months,
sum all pensionable compensation and divide by N. The highest resulting
average is the AMS.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(1-3) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Pensionable compensation includes base salary, longevity pay, shift
differentials. Excludes bonuses, expense reimbursements, severance.

• Anti-spiking provisions: unknown whether DERP caps year-over-year
salary increases in the AMS window.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-05\] \[HIGH\] Does DERP have anti-spiking provisions that cap
year-over-year salary increases in the AMS window?

**Test Implications:** Verify AMS matches hand calculations for all four
demo cases to the penny (after rounding strategy is applied).

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**4.3 --- RULE-LEAVE-PAYOUT**

**RULE-LEAVE-PAYOUT Leave Payout Inclusion**

**Rule Statement:** For members whose service begins on or before
December 31, 2009: unused sick and vacation leave paid out at separation
is treated as salary and included in the AMS calculation. Members hired
on or after January 1, 2010: leave payout is NOT included.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(15) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• The leave payout is added to the FINAL month\'s salary before AMS
window calculation. This can dramatically boost the AMS if the final
month falls within the highest window.

• Note: The hire date cutoff (Jan 1, 2010) does NOT align with tier
boundaries (Sep 1, 2004 / Jul 1, 2011). A Tier 2 member hired March 1,
2008 IS eligible. A Tier 2 member hired Feb 1, 2010 is NOT eligible.

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez (Case 1): hired 1997, eligible,
\$52,000 payout boosts final month. Jennifer Kim (Case 2): hired March
2008, eligible for leave payout (hired before Jan 1, 2010). David
Washington (Case 3): hired Sep 2012, NOT eligible. Test the hire-date
boundary independent of tier.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers (eligibility based on hire date, not
tier)

**4.4 --- RULE-FURLOUGH**

**RULE-FURLOUGH Furlough Impact on AMS**

**Rule Statement:** If furlough days fall within the AMS window, they
reduce pensionable salary for those months. Members may purchase
furlough days to negate this impact.

**Source:** RMC §18-402 (definitions), operational practice **⚠️
ASSUMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Furlough purchase mechanism exists but specific cost calculation and
process details are not fully documented in available RMC sections. This
rule is included for completeness but no demo case exercises it.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-FURLOUGH-01\] What is the cost formula for purchasing furlough
days? Is it the same actuarial methodology as service purchase?

**Test Implications:** No demo case currently exercises this. If
included in POC, would need a synthetic member with furlough in AMS
window to test before/after impact.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**4.5 --- RULE-BENEFIT-T1**

**RULE-BENEFIT-T1 Tier 1 Benefit Formula**

**Rule Statement:** Monthly Benefit = AMS × 2.0% × Total Service Years
(earned + purchased).

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(1) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez (Case 1): AMS × 0.02 × 28.75.
Verify to the penny against hand calculation.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 1

**4.6 --- RULE-BENEFIT-T2**

**RULE-BENEFIT-T2 Tier 2 Benefit Formula**

**Rule Statement:** Monthly Benefit = AMS × 1.5% × Total Service Years
(earned + purchased).

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(2) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim (Case 2): \$7,347.62 × 0.015 × 21.17
= \$2,332.96. Verify to the penny.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 2

**4.7 --- RULE-BENEFIT-T3**

**RULE-BENEFIT-T3 Tier 3 Benefit Formula**

**Rule Statement:** Monthly Benefit = AMS × 1.5% × Total Service Years
(earned + purchased).

**Source:** RMC §18-409(a)(3) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** David Washington (Case 3): verify against hand
calculation. Note: same multiplier as Tier 2 but different AMS window
(60 vs 36 months).

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3

**4.8 --- RULE-REDUCTION-APPLY**

**RULE-REDUCTION-APPLY Early Retirement Reduction Application**

**Rule Statement:** If early retirement, multiply unreduced benefit by
(1 - reduction_percentage). Reduction is permanent for lifetime.

**Source:** RMC §18-409(b) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim: \$2,332.96 × 0.70 = \$1,633.07.
David Washington: unreduced × 0.88.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers (when early retirement applies)

**4.9 --- RULE-ROUNDING**

**RULE-ROUNDING Calculation Rounding Strategy**

**Rule Statement:** Carry full precision through all intermediate
calculations. Round only the final monthly benefit amount to cents (2
decimal places). Use banker\'s rounding (round half to even).

**Source:** BUILD_HISTORY Decision 21 --- project decision, NOT
confirmed by DERP **⚠️ ASSUMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• DERP\'s actual rounding methodology is unknown. We have assumed
banker\'s rounding. DERP may use standard rounding (0.5 rounds up) or
truncation. This could cause penny-level differences.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-01\] \[CRITICAL\] What rounding methodology does DERP use?
Standard rounding, banker\'s rounding, or truncation? At what stage is
rounding applied?

**Test Implications:** Test cases at rounding boundaries (amounts ending
in exactly .X50). Compare results under each rounding method to quantify
impact.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 5: Payment Options & Spousal Consent**

Payment option selection determines the lifetime benefit structure. J&S
options reduce the member\'s benefit in exchange for survivor
protection. Spousal consent requirements protect marital interests. All
elections are irrevocable.

**5.0 --- Summary**

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**                   **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ----------------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-PAY-MAXIMUM              Maximum Benefit (Single    ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                                Life Annuity)                           

  RULE-JS-100                   100% Joint & Survivor      ✅ CONFIRMED 1 open
                                Option                                  

  RULE-JS-75                    75% Joint & Survivor       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                                Option                                  

  RULE-JS-50                    50% Joint & Survivor       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                                Option                                  

  RULE-JS-DEFAULT               Default Payment Option for ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                                Married Members                         

  RULE-SPOUSAL-CONSENT          Spousal Consent            ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                                Requirement                             

  RULE-BENEFICIARY-PREDECEASE   Beneficiary Predeceases    ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                                Member                                  
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**5.1 --- RULE-PAY-MAXIMUM**

**RULE-PAY-MAXIMUM Maximum Benefit (Single Life Annuity)**

**Rule Statement:** The maximum benefit is the full calculated monthly
amount with no survivor protection. Payments continue for member\'s
lifetime only; all payments cease upon death.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Verify maximum equals the formula output (after
reduction if applicable, after DRO split if applicable).

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.2 --- RULE-JS-100**

**RULE-JS-100 100% Joint & Survivor Option**

**Rule Statement:** Reduced benefit that, upon member\'s death,
continues at 100% of the member\'s reduced amount to the designated
beneficiary for life.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a)(1) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Actuarial factors for J&S options are NOT available. POC uses
placeholder factors (100% J&S: 0.8850). Actual factors depend on member
age, beneficiary age, and DERP\'s actuarial tables.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-CALC-04\] \[CRITICAL\] Can DERP provide the actuarial factor
tables for J&S calculations? Factors by member age, beneficiary age, and
J&S percentage.

**Test Implications:** Using placeholder factors: verify calculation is
maximum × factor. When real factors obtained, recalculate all demo
cases.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.3 --- RULE-JS-75**

**RULE-JS-75 75% Joint & Survivor Option**

**Rule Statement:** Reduced benefit that, upon member\'s death,
continues at 75% of the member\'s reduced amount to the designated
beneficiary for life.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a)(1) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Placeholder factor: 0.9150. Same dependency on actual actuarial
tables.

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez (Case 1) elects 75% J&S with
Elena. Verify: member benefit = maximum × 0.9150; survivor = member
benefit × 0.75.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.4 --- RULE-JS-50**

**RULE-JS-50 50% Joint & Survivor Option**

**Rule Statement:** Reduced benefit that, upon member\'s death,
continues at 50% of the member\'s reduced amount to the designated
beneficiary for life.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a)(1) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Placeholder factor: 0.9450. Default option for married members who
fail to make an election.

**Test Implications:** Verify: member benefit = maximum × 0.9450;
survivor = member benefit × 0.50.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.5 --- RULE-JS-DEFAULT**

**RULE-JS-DEFAULT Default Payment Option for Married Members**

**Rule Statement:** If a married member fails to elect a payment option,
the default is 50% J&S with spouse as beneficiary.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a)(1) --- confirmed in RMC verification v3 **✅
CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: married member with no election recorded →
system defaults to 50% J&S. Unmarried member with no election → Maximum.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.6 --- RULE-SPOUSAL-CONSENT**

**RULE-SPOUSAL-CONSENT Spousal Consent Requirement**

**Rule Statement:** If married, spouse must be designated as beneficiary
for at least 50% J&S option UNLESS spouse provides notarized written
consent to waive this right. Consent form cannot be signed/submitted
more than 90 days before first payment. Consent is irrevocable.

**Source:** RMC §18-410(a)(1), Spousal Consent At Retirement form **✅
CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: married member elects Maximum without
spousal consent → blocked. Married member elects 50% J&S with non-spouse
beneficiary → requires consent. Married member elects 75% J&S with
spouse → no consent needed. 90-day timing validation.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**5.7 --- RULE-BENEFICIARY-PREDECEASE**

**RULE-BENEFICIARY-PREDECEASE Beneficiary Predeceases Member**

**Rule Statement:** If J&S beneficiary predeceases the member, the
member\'s benefit is increased prospectively to the Maximum (single
life) amount. Member may NOT select a new beneficiary.

**Source:** Retirement Application Page 2 --- explicit statement on form
**✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: beneficiary death event → member benefit
recalculated to Maximum. No new beneficiary election allowed.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 6: Domestic Relations Orders (DRO)**

DRO rules govern the division of pension benefits pursuant to court
orders from divorce proceedings. The critical principle is sequencing:
DRO split happens FIRST, before payment option selection. The alternate
payee\'s amount is independent of the member\'s J&S election.

**6.0 --- Summary**

  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**              **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ------------------------ -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-DRO-MARITAL-SHARE   DRO Marital Share          ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                           Calculation                             

  RULE-DRO-SEQUENCE        DRO Split Before Payment   ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                           Option                                  

  RULE-DRO-METHODS         DRO Division Methods       ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions

  RULE-DRO-NO-IPR          DRO Alternate Payee IPR    ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                           Exclusion                               

  RULE-DRO-NO-HEALTH       DRO Alternate Payee Health ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                           Insurance Exclusion                     

  RULE-DRO-COLA            DRO and COLA Applicability ⚠️ ASSUMED   1 open
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**6.1 --- RULE-DRO-MARITAL-SHARE**

**RULE-DRO-MARITAL-SHARE DRO Marital Share Calculation**

**Rule Statement:** Marital fraction = service credit during marriage /
total service credit at retirement. Marital share = maximum benefit ×
marital fraction. Alternate payee receives their awarded percentage of
the marital share.

**Source:** RMC §18-418(b), doc07-domestic-relations-orders **✅
CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Service during marriage is calculated from marriage date to divorce
date, overlapping with employment period only. If marriage predates
employment, marital service starts at hire date.

**Test Implications:** Case 4: marriage Aug 15, 1999 to Nov 3, 2017 =
18.25 years of marital service. Fraction: 18.25/28.75 = 63.48%. Patricia
gets 40% of marital share.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**6.2 --- RULE-DRO-SEQUENCE**

**RULE-DRO-SEQUENCE DRO Split Before Payment Option**

**Rule Statement:** DRO split is calculated on the Maximum (single life)
benefit FIRST. The member\'s remaining benefit (after DRO) is then
subject to J&S option selection. The alternate payee\'s amount is NOT
affected by the member\'s payment option election.

**Source:** RMC §18-418(b), doc07 Section 6 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Case 4: DRO split from maximum, THEN 75% J&S
applied to remainder. Patricia\'s \$1,553.24 is unaffected by Robert\'s
J&S election. This is the single most important sequencing rule for DRO
cases.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**6.3 --- RULE-DRO-METHODS**

**RULE-DRO-METHODS DRO Division Methods**

**Rule Statement:** DROs may divide benefits by: (a) percentage of
marital share (most common), (b) fixed dollar amount, or (c) present
value offset (no ongoing plan involvement).

**Source:** RMC §18-418(b), doc07 Section 4 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• POC implements percentage-of-marital-share method (Case 4). Fixed
dollar method is simpler but less common. Present value offset requires
no system calculation.

**Test Implications:** Case 4 demonstrates percentage method. Future
test cases could add fixed-dollar method.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**6.4 --- RULE-DRO-NO-IPR**

**RULE-DRO-NO-IPR DRO Alternate Payee IPR Exclusion**

**Rule Statement:** Former spouse receiving DRO benefits is NOT eligible
for IPR (Insurance Premium Reduction).

**Source:** RMC §18-418(b)(8) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Case 4 calculation document originally included Patricia\'s IPR. This
must be removed per RMC verification v3.

**Test Implications:** Case 4: verify Patricia does NOT receive IPR.
Robert still receives IPR on his earned service.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**6.5 --- RULE-DRO-NO-HEALTH**

**RULE-DRO-NO-HEALTH DRO Alternate Payee Health Insurance Exclusion**

**Rule Statement:** Former spouse is NOT eligible for DERP health
insurance benefits.

**Source:** RMC §18-418(b)(8) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Verify workspace does not show health insurance
options for alternate payees.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**6.6 --- RULE-DRO-COLA**

**RULE-DRO-COLA DRO and COLA Applicability**

**Rule Statement:** Whether the alternate payee\'s share participates in
future COLAs depends on the specific DRO language.

**Source:** doc07 Section 4 **⚠️ ASSUMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• COLA participation for alternate payees is determined by DRO order
language, not plan default. Each DRO must be reviewed individually.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-DRO-03\] What is DERP\'s default position on COLA for DRO
alternate payees when the court order is silent?

**Test Implications:** Test both scenarios: COLA-participating and
non-participating alternate payee shares.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 7: Supplemental Benefits (IPR & Death Benefit)**

Supplemental benefits are calculated alongside the core retirement
benefit. IPR provides health insurance assistance. The lump-sum death
benefit is an irrevocable election made at retirement.

**7.0 --- Summary**

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**            **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  ---------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-IPR               Insurance Premium          ✅ CONFIRMED 2 assumptions
                         Reduction                               

  RULE-DEATH-NORMAL      Lump-Sum Death Benefit     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                         (Normal/Rule of N)                      

  RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T12   Lump-Sum Death Benefit     ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                         (Early Retirement, Tiers 1              
                         & 2)                                    

  RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T3    Lump-Sum Death Benefit     ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                         (Early Retirement, Tier 3)              

  RULE-DEATH-ELECTION    Death Benefit Election     ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-DEATH-REEMPLOY    Death Benefit              ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                         Re-Employment Exclusion                 
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**7.1 --- RULE-IPR**

**RULE-IPR Insurance Premium Reduction**

**Rule Statement:** IPR provides a monthly supplement: \$12.50 per year
of earned service (non-Medicare eligible) or \$6.25 per year of earned
service (Medicare eligible). Purchased service is EXCLUDED from IPR
calculation.

**Source:** RMC §18-412, process definition **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• IPR uses EARNED service only. This is consistent with the
purchased-service exclusion principle.

• Medicare eligibility is typically at age 65, but members may become
Medicare-eligible earlier through disability. For POC, we assume age 65
= Medicare transition point.

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez: 28.75 earned years × \$12.50 =
\$359.38/month (pre-Medicare). Test transition to \$6.25 rate at
Medicare eligibility.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**7.2 --- RULE-DEATH-NORMAL**

**RULE-DEATH-NORMAL Lump-Sum Death Benefit (Normal/Rule of N)**

**Rule Statement:** For normal retirement, Rule of 75, Rule of 85, or
Disability Retirement after age 65: lump-sum death benefit is \$5,000.

**Source:** RMC §18-411(d)(1-2), Retirement Application Part C **✅
CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Must retire directly from active service to be eligible. Deferred
retirees are NOT eligible.

**Test Implications:** Robert Martinez (Cases 1 & 4): \$5,000. Verify
deferred members get \$0.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**7.3 --- RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T12**

**RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T12 Lump-Sum Death Benefit (Early Retirement, Tiers 1
& 2)**

**Rule Statement:** For early retirement: \$5,000 minus \$250 per
completed year under age 65. RMC provides statutory dollar-amount table
by integer age (age 55 = \$2,500, age 56 = \$2,750, \..., age 64 =
\$4,750).

**Source:** RMC §18-411(d)(1) --- statutory table **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• Integer-age approach confirmed by statutory dollar-amount table (not
formula-based; explicit amounts per age).

**Test Implications:** Jennifer Kim (Case 2): age 55, \$2,500. Test each
age from 55-64.

**Tier Applicability:** Tiers 1 and 2

**7.4 --- RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T3**

**RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T3 Lump-Sum Death Benefit (Early Retirement, Tier
3)**

**Rule Statement:** For early retirement: \$5,000 minus \$500 per
completed year under age 65. Statutory table: age 60 = \$2,500, age 61 =
\$3,000, \..., age 64 = \$4,500.

**Source:** RMC §18-411(d)(2) --- statutory table **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** David Washington (Case 3): age 63, \$4,000. Test
each age from 60-64.

**Tier Applicability:** Tier 3

**7.5 --- RULE-DEATH-ELECTION**

**RULE-DEATH-ELECTION Death Benefit Election**

**Rule Statement:** Lump-sum death benefit may be drawn in 50 or 100
equal monthly installments. This is an irrevocable election made at
retirement. Disbursement is concurrent with monthly retirement benefit.
Member may also elect NOT to draw the death benefit.

**Source:** RMC §18-411(d), Retirement Application Part C **✅
CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: three election options (50 installments,
100 installments, do not draw). Verify installment amount = total /
elected installments. Verify irrevocability.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**7.6 --- RULE-DEATH-REEMPLOY**

**RULE-DEATH-REEMPLOY Death Benefit Re-Employment Exclusion**

**Rule Statement:** Re-employed retirees are NOT entitled to a
subsequent death benefit. The original amount from their first
retirement applies.

**Source:** RMC §18-408(j) **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Test: re-employed member\'s death benefit =
original retirement amount, not recalculated.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Category 8: Process & Timing Rules**

Process rules govern application deadlines, payment processing, and the
irrevocability of elections. These rules enforce the administrative
framework within which benefit calculations operate.

**8.0 --- Summary**

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Rule ID**           **Rule Name**              **Status**   **Open Items**
  --------------------- -------------------------- ------------ ----------------
  RULE-APP-DEADLINE     Application Filing         ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions
                        Deadline                                

  RULE-NOTARIZATION     Application Notarization   ✅ CONFIRMED ---
                        Requirement                             

  RULE-PAYMENT-CUTOFF   Payment Processing Cutoff  ⚠️ ASSUMED   1 open

  RULE-EFFECTIVE-DATE   Retirement Effective Date  ✅ CONFIRMED 1 assumptions

  RULE-IRREVOCABILITY   Election Irrevocability    ✅ CONFIRMED ---

  RULE-COLA             Cost of Living Adjustment  ✅ CONFIRMED 2 assumptions
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**8.1 --- RULE-APP-DEADLINE**

**RULE-APP-DEADLINE Application Filing Deadline**

**Rule Statement:** Retirement application must be received within 30
calendar days of last day worked. Missing this deadline results in
automatic deferred member classification with no appeal or extension.

**Source:** RMC §18-402(10), §18-408 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• 30 \'calendar days\' (not business days). Application must be
RECEIVED, not postmarked.

**Test Implications:** All four demo cases pass (applications filed well
within 30 days). Test boundary: day 30 = accepted; day 31 = deferred.
Test: what constitutes \'received\' (mail vs. in-person vs. electronic).

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**8.2 --- RULE-NOTARIZATION**

**RULE-NOTARIZATION Application Notarization Requirement**

**Rule Statement:** Retirement application must bear notarized signature
before the application can be processed.

**Source:** Retirement Application form, Spousal Consent form **✅
CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** Application without notarization → blocks
progression past Stage 1 (Intake).

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**8.3 --- RULE-PAYMENT-CUTOFF**

**RULE-PAYMENT-CUTOFF Payment Processing Cutoff**

**Rule Statement:** Complete application package received by the 15th of
the month prior to retirement effective date → first payment on time.
Received after 15th → first payment delayed; combined first/second
payment in following month.

**Source:** Operational practice, Retirement Application instructions
**⚠️ ASSUMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• This is documented in DERP member materials but the specific cutoff
date (15th) is not in the RMC. It is an operational/administrative
deadline, not a statutory one.

**❓ Open Items:**

• \[Q-PROCESS-01\] Is the 15th-of-month cutoff a hard rule or a
guideline? Does it apply to the month before the effective date
specifically?

**Test Implications:** All four demo cases pass (complete packages
before 15th). Test: package received March 16 for April 1 effective date
→ first payment delayed.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**8.4 --- RULE-EFFECTIVE-DATE**

**RULE-EFFECTIVE-DATE Retirement Effective Date**

**Rule Statement:** Retirement is effective on the first day of a
calendar month following the last day of employment.

**Source:** RMC §18-408, operational practice **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• If last day worked is March 31, effective date is April 1. If last day
worked is March 15, effective date is still April 1 (next
first-of-month).

**Test Implications:** Test various termination dates within a month.
All should produce first-of-next-month effective date.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**8.5 --- RULE-IRREVOCABILITY**

**RULE-IRREVOCABILITY Election Irrevocability**

**Rule Statement:** Payment option election, death benefit election, and
spousal consent waiver are all irrevocable once retirement payments
begin. J&S beneficiary cannot be changed after retirement.

**Source:** RMC §18-410, Retirement Application form **✅ CONFIRMED**

**Test Implications:** System must enforce: no election changes after
Stage 5 (Payment Initiation). Pre-Stage 5 changes should be allowed.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**8.6 --- RULE-COLA**

**RULE-COLA Cost of Living Adjustment**

**Rule Statement:** COLA is discretionary, approved by the DERP Board.
No automatic formula. Maximum 5% per year or CPI (whichever is less).
First eligible January 1 of the second calendar year after retirement.

**Source:** RMC §18-414 **✅ CONFIRMED**

**⚠️ Assumptions Surfaced:**

• COLA is board-discretionary, not calculated by the system. The system
tracks eligibility dates and applies board-approved amounts. No
calculation engine component needed for COLA determination.

• For POC, COLA is acknowledged in rules but not exercised in demo cases
(all retire in 2026, first COLA eligibility would be January 1, 2028).

**Test Implications:** Test: COLA eligibility date correctly calculated
(Jan 1 of 2nd calendar year post-retirement). April 2026 retiree → first
eligible Jan 1, 2028.

**Tier Applicability:** All tiers

**Appendix A: Assumptions Register**

Every assumption embedded in the rules inventory, with risk
classification. HIGH risk assumptions could cause calculation errors.
MEDIUM risk assumptions may cause presentation or workflow issues. LOW
risk assumptions affect only seed data or non-critical features.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Related Rule**         **Assumption**                              **Risk**
  ------------------------ ------------------------------------------- -------------
  RULE-TIER-1              The \'terminates after Dec 31, 1999\'       LOW
                           clause means members who separated before   
                           2000 are under a prior plan provision. Seed 
                           data must not generate Tier 1 members with  
                           termination before Jan 1, 2000.             

  RULE-TIER-3              Tier is determined by INITIAL hire date,    MEDIUM
                           not most recent. For re-employment after    
                           retirement, RMC §18-408(j)(1) confirms new  
                           service earns under Tier 3 formula          
                           regardless of original tier, but original   
                           benefit retains original tier.              

  RULE-CONTRIB-EE          This is the current rate only. Historical   LOW
                           rates needed for seed data (8.45% since at  
                           least 2014; earlier rates unknown). For the 
                           rules engine, only current rate matters.    

  RULE-CONTRIB-ER          Same historical rate caveat as employee     LOW
                           contribution. Approximate: \~11% pre-2012,  
                           scaling to 17.95% current. These are        
                           estimates for seed data, not verified       
                           rates.                                      

  RULE-SVC-EARNED          Service credit calculation method           MEDIUM
                           (year-month vs. exact day) is NOT specified 
                           in the RMC. Our demo cases use year-month   
                           (months/12, e.g., 28 yrs 9 mo = 28.75). If  
                           DERP uses exact days, Robert Martinez would 
                           be 28.797 instead of 28.75.                 

  RULE-VESTING             For POC scope, all synthetic members are    MEDIUM
                           post-1987 hires, so 5-year vesting applies. 
                           The 10-year pre-1987 rule is documented but 
                           not expected in demo cases.                 

  RULE-VESTING             Vesting uses credited service (earned only? MEDIUM
                           or earned + purchased?). RMC §18-415(a)     
                           says purchased service cannot be used for   
                           vesting, so vesting is earned-only.         

  RULE-RULE-OF-75          Rule uses EARNED service only (purchased    MEDIUM
                           excluded per RULE-SVC-PURCHASED). Confirmed 
                           by §18-415(a).                              

  RULE-RULE-OF-75          If member terminates after meeting the sum  MEDIUM
                           but before reaching age 55, they must wait  
                           until age 55 to apply. They do NOT lose the 
                           Rule --- they just cannot collect until     
                           minimum age.                                

  RULE-RULE-OF-85          Same partial-year calculation dependency as MEDIUM
                           Rule of 75.                                 

  RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T12    Integer-age approach confirmed by RMC       MEDIUM
                           statutory table. No monthly proration.      
                           Decision 18 assumed completed years only    
                           --- RMC table confirms this by listing      
                           integer ages only.                          

  RULE-EARLY-REDUCE-T3     Same integer-age approach as Tiers 1/2.     MEDIUM
                           Note: Tier 3 table increments are 6% (not   
                           uniform --- 70, 76, 82, 88, 94, 100).       

  RULE-DEFERRED            Automatic deferred classification after     MEDIUM
                           30-day deadline is confirmed by RMC --- no  
                           appeal or extension in statute.             

  RULE-ELIG-HIERARCHY      A member who qualifies for both normal      MEDIUM
                           retirement (age 65+) and Rule of 75 should  
                           be classified as normal retirement. The     
                           hierarchy prevents double-classification    
                           but the benefit amount is identical.        

  RULE-AMS-WINDOW          Period must be consecutive (no gaps).       MEDIUM
                           System must search ALL possible windows to  
                           find the highest average.                   

  RULE-AMS-WINDOW          How partial months at start/end of          MEDIUM
                           employment are handled is not specified in  
                           the RMC. Our assumption: only complete      
                           months are included.                        

  RULE-AMS-CALC            Pensionable compensation includes base      MEDIUM
                           salary, longevity pay, shift differentials. 
                           Excludes bonuses, expense reimbursements,   
                           severance.                                  

  RULE-AMS-CALC            Anti-spiking provisions: unknown whether    MEDIUM
                           DERP caps year-over-year salary increases   
                           in the AMS window.                          

  RULE-LEAVE-PAYOUT        The leave payout is added to the FINAL      MEDIUM
                           month\'s salary before AMS window           
                           calculation. This can dramatically boost    
                           the AMS if the final month falls within the 
                           highest window.                             

  RULE-LEAVE-PAYOUT        Note: The hire date cutoff (Jan 1, 2010)    MEDIUM
                           does NOT align with tier boundaries (Sep 1, 
                           2004 / Jul 1, 2011). A Tier 2 member hired  
                           March 1, 2008 IS eligible. A Tier 2 member  
                           hired Feb 1, 2010 is NOT eligible.          

  RULE-FURLOUGH            Furlough purchase mechanism exists but      MEDIUM
                           specific cost calculation and process       
                           details are not fully documented in         
                           available RMC sections. This rule is        
                           included for completeness but no demo case  
                           exercises it.                               

  RULE-ROUNDING            DERP\'s actual rounding methodology is      HIGH
                           unknown. We have assumed banker\'s          
                           rounding. DERP may use standard rounding    
                           (0.5 rounds up) or truncation. This could   
                           cause penny-level differences.              

  RULE-JS-100              Actuarial factors for J&S options are NOT   MEDIUM
                           available. POC uses placeholder factors     
                           (100% J&S: 0.8850). Actual factors depend   
                           on member age, beneficiary age, and DERP\'s 
                           actuarial tables.                           

  RULE-JS-75               Placeholder factor: 0.9150. Same dependency MEDIUM
                           on actual actuarial tables.                 

  RULE-JS-50               Placeholder factor: 0.9450. Default option  MEDIUM
                           for married members who fail to make an     
                           election.                                   

  RULE-DRO-MARITAL-SHARE   Service during marriage is calculated from  MEDIUM
                           marriage date to divorce date, overlapping  
                           with employment period only. If marriage    
                           predates employment, marital service starts 
                           at hire date.                               

  RULE-DRO-METHODS         POC implements percentage-of-marital-share  MEDIUM
                           method (Case 4). Fixed dollar method is     
                           simpler but less common. Present value      
                           offset requires no system calculation.      

  RULE-DRO-NO-IPR          Case 4 calculation document originally      MEDIUM
                           included Patricia\'s IPR. This must be      
                           removed per RMC verification v3.            

  RULE-DRO-COLA            COLA participation for alternate payees is  MEDIUM
                           determined by DRO order language, not plan  
                           default. Each DRO must be reviewed          
                           individually.                               

  RULE-IPR                 IPR uses EARNED service only. This is       MEDIUM
                           consistent with the purchased-service       
                           exclusion principle.                        

  RULE-IPR                 Medicare eligibility is typically at age    MEDIUM
                           65, but members may become                  
                           Medicare-eligible earlier through           
                           disability. For POC, we assume age 65 =     
                           Medicare transition point.                  

  RULE-DEATH-NORMAL        Must retire directly from active service to MEDIUM
                           be eligible. Deferred retirees are NOT      
                           eligible.                                   

  RULE-DEATH-EARLY-T12     Integer-age approach confirmed by statutory MEDIUM
                           dollar-amount table (not formula-based;     
                           explicit amounts per age).                  

  RULE-APP-DEADLINE        30 \'calendar days\' (not business days).   MEDIUM
                           Application must be RECEIVED, not           
                           postmarked.                                 

  RULE-PAYMENT-CUTOFF      This is documented in DERP member materials MEDIUM
                           but the specific cutoff date (15th) is not  
                           in the RMC. It is an                        
                           operational/administrative deadline, not a  
                           statutory one.                              

  RULE-EFFECTIVE-DATE      If last day worked is March 31, effective   MEDIUM
                           date is April 1. If last day worked is      
                           March 15, effective date is still April 1   
                           (next first-of-month).                      

  RULE-COLA                COLA is board-discretionary, not calculated MEDIUM
                           by the system. The system tracks            
                           eligibility dates and applies               
                           board-approved amounts. No calculation      
                           engine component needed for COLA            
                           determination.                              

  RULE-COLA                For POC, COLA is acknowledged in rules but  MEDIUM
                           not exercised in demo cases (all retire in  
                           2026, first COLA eligibility would be       
                           January 1, 2028).                           
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

